		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">JEWS IN <hi rend="underline"><placeName>TURKEY</placeName>.</hi></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Smyrna</placeName>&#44; <date>January 24&#44; 1855</date>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>ISAAC LEESER&#44; ESQ.</addressee>&#58;&#8212;Dear Sir&#8212;<persName>Mr. Mitchell</persName>&#44; of your<lb/> city&#44; <sic>s</sic> friend of yours&#44; was several days detained in<lb/> this city&#44; and fortunately I became acquainted with<lb/> him.  He requested me to address a letter to you&#44; giv&#45;<lb/>ing you some information respecting the Jews in this<lb/> place and in this vicinity.  This I readily assented<lb/> to do&#59; but I <sic>mustconfess</sic> to negligence in allowing so<lb/> many weeks to pass without fulfilling my promise.  I<lb/> shall not set it down entirely as negligence&#59; for I<lb/> have been so fully occupied that I have not found time<lb/> to write many letters to personal relatives&#44; which I<lb/> acknowledge as due from me.  But as I have at present<lb/> no time to spare I will not prolong to apologize.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I came to this country in the year <date>1850</date>&#44; as mission&#45;<lb/>ary to the Jews of the A.B.C.F.M.  Two years we were<lb/> in <placeName>Thessalonica</placeName>&#44; six months&#44; on account of health&#44; in<lb/> <placeName>Constantinople</placeName>&#44; and the rest of the time in this city.<lb/>  While in <placeName>Thessalonica</placeName> I made several short tours&#8212;ra&#45;<lb/>ther&#44; one long one and one short one.  I will give you<lb/> the names of the Jewish places and their population&#44;<lb/> as nearly as I can be tolerably certain of correctness.<lb/>  You know how difficult it is to obtain exact statistics.</p>
				<p>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</p>
				<p>&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#8212;&#45;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr. Mitchell</persName> said he would send me a copy of your<lb/> paper&#44; which I am sure will be very valuable to us&#44;<lb/> in giving extracts from it&#44; and information respecting<lb/> the Jews in <placeName>America</placeName>.  The very appearance of your<lb/> beautiful journal &#40;of which <persName>Mr. M.</persName> showed me a copy&#41;<lb/> would be a marvel to our Jewish friends here&#44; when told<lb/> that it was published by a Jew.  I told <persName>Mr. Mitchell</persName><lb/> that I should value very highly the back numbers of<lb/> your periodical&#59; he said he would inquire if they could<lb/> be furnished&#44; and at what price.  I trust he will not<lb/> forget it&#44; or that you will be so kind as to inform me<lb/> directly.</p>
				<p>If you have any particular inquiries to make&#44; I shall</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p><del>&#63;</del> be most happy to<lb/> answer them as far as I am able.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your work is arduous&#44; but I trust you will see the<lb/> benefit resulting to your people.  May the Lord bless<lb/> you&#59; and I remain yours&#44; truly&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">J. W. PARSONS</persName>.</p>
				<p><hi rend="underline">Occ. Vol. XIII&#44; <sic>page45</sic>&#59; <date>Nissan 5615&#44; April 1855</date>.     </hi></p>
		
